  "answer": "Co‑extruding a polyolefin elastomer layer with an EVOH barrier and then applying an OTS topcoat typically requires equipment that can handle the high melt temperatures of both the elastomer (≈250–330 °C) and the EVOH (≈300–350 °C). A standard twin‑screw extruder that is only rated for commodity PE/PP (≤200 °C) will usually not provide sufficient heating capacity or barrel length to achieve uniform melt and avoid degradation of the EVOH. Therefore, a high‑temperature capable twin‑screw extruder with at least four heating zones, an L/D ratio >24, and corrosion‑resistant barrel material is recommended for the co‑extrusion step.\n\nAfter extrusion/lamination, the OTS topcoat is normally applied in a separate coating station (e.g., spray or dip coat) that can control temperature, humidity, and provide a clean atmosphere. This station is not part of the extruder but must be integrated into the line to apply the silane uniformly without exposing it to excessive heat that could hydrolyze the trichlorosilane.\n\nIn short: use a high‑temperature twin‑screw extruder (or a dedicated co‑extrusion unit) for the multilayer film, and add a dedicated OTS coating station afterward.",
